					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7758789#post-4064969</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7758789/scp-4149#post-4064969</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Thu, 22 Nov 2018 06:07:03 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Gabriel McQueen</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>4558836</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <blockquote> <p>contains 76 art pieces across various mediums, including fine art, performance art, modern art, and sculptures</p> </blockquote> <p>This phrasing has some issues. &quot;Art pieces&quot; is fine, but &quot;artworks&quot; feels more natural to me. More problematic is the second part. The medium of an artwork is generally understood to be the material[s] it is made from. &quot;Fine art&quot; connotes any art which is made with skill and training for purely aesthetic purposes, to differentiate it from untrained/outsider art, commercial art, etc., and can be made in any medium. Performance art could be considered a medium, so that's fine. Modern art refers to artwork made roughly from the end of the 19th century into the 1970s which exemplifies certain traits, mostly a departure from realism. It's a movement, not a medium. Sculpture is neither a medium nor a movement, but is any kind of fully 3d artwork. If the gallery contains all these types of art, that's fine and great, but these are basically four different types of sometimes overlapping categories.</p> <p>It's one of my favorite things to read descriptions of artworks in fiction, so I'd love it if any of the specific artworks here were described.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
